{
  "texts": [
    "Ghosh et al. [52] showed high bias from simulated scenarios without real patient interactions.",
    "This could lead to overestimated accuracy and applicability in real-world settings.",
    "The studies of Schneider et al. [46] and Faqar-Uz-Zaman et al.",
    "[45] showed a low risk of bias according to the RoB Tool, with detailed methodology and statistical analysis.",
    "In contrast, the study of Wang et al. [29] showed a risk of bias due to the absence of intention-to-treat analysis and participants being aware of the intervention (Appendix 3, Figure 6), which could skew results by excluding non-completers and altering participant behavior."
  ]
}